{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/blog/capture-dom-element-screenshots-in-chrome/","result":{"data":{"post":{"html":"<p>Whenever I <a href=\"https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/creating-a-pull-request\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">submit a PR</a> for a UI change, I like to include a screenshot or two in order to aid the my teammates in reviewing the code, especially when it‚Äôs CSS changes. Ideally there would be a <a href=\"https://www.netlify.com/blog/2016/07/20/introducing-deploy-previews-in-netlify/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Deploy preview</a>, but not everything is running on <a href=\"https://www.netlify.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Netlify</a> (yet).</p>\n<p>Usually I only need a screenshot of the section of the page that actually changed. So I hit <code class=\"language-text\">Cmd+Shift+4</code> (on my Mac) and select the a section containing the UI. Boom screenshot. Well for now on, thanks to a tweet from <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bitandbang\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Tierney Cyren</a>, I can be more precise in my screenshot. In Chrome, Edge or any Chromium-based environment, I can get a screenshot of <em>just</em> the element in the DOM:</p>\n<blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\">two quick things that I don&#39;t think enough people know about:<br><br>1. there&#39;s a command palette in DevTools - CMD/CTRL + Shift + P<br>2. you can take screenshots of a single node from the palette <a href=\"https://t.co/NpoZQpAquT\">pic.twitter.com/NpoZQpAquT</a></p>&mdash; pay essential workers like they‚Äôre essential (@bitandbang) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bitandbang/status/1253737729298436098?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">April 24, 2020</a></blockquote>\n<p>If you can‚Äôt watch the video, here are the steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Inspect the DOM element to highlight it in the Elements panel of the DevTools</li>\n<li>Press <code class=\"language-text\">Cmd/Ctrl+Shift+P</code> to pull up the DevTools command palette (also something new I just learned about!)</li>\n<li>Choose ‚ÄúCapture <strong>node</strong> screenshot‚Äù</li>\n<li>Save the file</li>\n</ol>\n<p>That‚Äôs it!</p>\n<p>But it gets even better because this process is even <strong>easier</strong> in Firefox. Once in the Element inspector, right-click on the element. There‚Äôs a ‚ÄúScreenshot Node‚Äù option right there in the menu! üéâ</p>\n<p>Now all of your PRs will get immediate üö¢ thanks to your beautiful screenshots. üòÇ</p>\n<p>Keep learning my friends. ü§ì</p>","excerpt":"Whenever I submit a PR for a UI change, I like to include a screenshot or two in order to aid the my teammates in reviewing the code‚Ä¶","timeToRead":2,"wordCount":{"words":214},"fields":{"slug":"/capture-dom-element-screenshots-in-chrome/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Capture DOM element screenshots in Chrome","shortDescription":"How to create a screenshot of a DOM element in Chromium-based DevTools","tags":["devtools","chrome","edge","chromium"],"category":"Web Development","date":"April 24, 2020","dateIso":"2020-04-24"}},"categoryPosts":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"dd80c30a-8173-5061-a506-fe52d380b4ec","frontmatter":{"title":"How to create an SVG gradient loading spinner","shortDescription":"How to add a gradient along an SVG circular arc path to create a loading spinner","tags":["svg","animations"],"date":"September 12, 2021","hero":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"tracedSVG":"data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20width='400'%20height='267'%20viewBox='0%200%20400%20267'%20preserveAspectRatio='none'%3e%3cpath%20d='M26%2027c-6%203-8%209-8%2030%200%2017%201%2023%204%2023l2%201c0%202%209%204%2013%203a147%20147%200%200143%203l16%201h16v-4l1-4%205-1c2-1%205-2%2011-2%208%200%209%200%2012-3l3-5%201-2c4-1%204-24%200-33-3-6-9-8-20-7a787%20787%200%2001-99%200m241%2076l-2%2